Work History

Caterpillar (Full Time) Aug 2014-Present

During this time my primary role has been Software Architect/Developer.

Currently I only have two machine software projects in production. This software was originally created by another team, but I took ownership of this software in 2015 and added a few new machine configurations, fixed a host of current production software issues, patched hardware issues using software logic, added safety interlock logic for improved user safety, added calibration support for factory technicians, and added diagnostic reporting capability.

My current project is by far one of the most complicated I have worked on and involves several applications, leveraged free software packages/environments, and provides a touch screen interface via full graphics display using HTML5 technology on an embedded platform running a Linux Operating System.

I have worked in C, C++, C#, HTML, CSS, JavaScript, Java, PHP, Python, Perl, batch, bash, and worked with makefiles, buildroot, virtual environments, and visual programming tools. I am very well versed in J1939 communication, and familiar with other data transportation methods (HTTP/XHR, FTP, SPI, I2C, Serial, USB, Bluetooth). I have programmed applications on embedded devices, and deployed applications to Operating Systems including: Windows 7-10, Android, and Linux.

I would say my current role is somewhere between a full stack developer and a software architect, and more days than not I assume both roles. I must comply with company standards in project documentation, releases, version control, repeatable builds, as well as meet customer requirements. I am accustomed to git version control, merging, and general software and version control maintenance activities. We use a system to track our activities and builds, which includes company standard release notes formats to drive commonality. I also adhere to company display standards regarding icon quality, text sizes, fonts, colors, etc, also driving visual continuity between programs.

I provide robust solutions that reduce workload by creating reusable libraries and classes, as well as provide application level support in order to drive program requirements to a production environment. For this program I have created a dynamic menu class, configurable by the application layer, and several layers that run on top of this layer in order to provide a dynamic user interface using an external and custom J1939 device to allow a user to traverse the application without using the touch interface. Understanding the complexity of requirements and providing flexible and repeatable solutions are a day to day activity for me. Our high velocity development does not allow for waste, so the more adaptable the software is the easier it is to meet our deadlines. This is but one of many solutions I have provide during my time here, and will likely not be the last.

Caterpillar (Contract via Belcan) Feb 2010-Aug 2014

My primary role during this time was to provide lab support for several machine software programs. During this time I integrated simulation equipment to provide electronic signals need for mimicking a machine's electronic system. I also integrated subsystems and components in order to facilitate machine software testing in a safe environment. During this time I was responsible for procuring everything we needed to get our lab up and running and keeping it maintained so we could meet our software requirements on schedule. Just before assuming my software role I built myself a manual test bench which I am still using today.

The test bench that I built.


My secondary role was to help with factory support. This often entailed deducing electronic control module failures, harness issues, and component failures. This also entailed communicating this issues to the manufacturer and coordinating failures with our product health team. This role also meant sometimes having to work on customer sites in order to troubleshoot issues that a normal field technician would not have the tools or knowledge to do.

I also spent roughly a year and half or more working on a user interface controlled simulation boxes using Arduinos and a GHI controller. It was nothing more than a proof of concept, of being able to configure and save initial values being simulated to a machine system. We had PWM, STB/STG/OPEN, and active analog signals controlled by this device. I also worked on a Sauer Danfoss Plus 1 Guide Tool, a visual programming tool, to reverse engineer a machine in current production in an effort to reduce control costs. This never made it to production due to hardware and timeline risks. I also worked on a few CAN/J1939 projects, two of which ended up on an Android application of their own. This was mainly research and development into some 3rd party technologies. I also have made a few factory support J1939 devices to communicate with various electronic control modules to provide end of line testing. It was also around this time I inadvertently setup others for what would become my current project. After losing a few people that were picked up for that project, I stepped in to drive the program forward to production.

It was during this time I completed my B.S. in Computer Science at Southwestern College.

USAF (Active Duty) Oct 2003- Oct 2009

My primary role during my tour in the USAF was an Avionics Technician. During the end of this time I held a team leader position in my back-shop area and reported directly to the shop supervisor. Alternately I would also serve as the shop floor leader when ranking non-commissioned officers where not available. I held a few extra duties during this time, namely our flight's training manager, safety coordinator, and environmental manager. Probably my most remembered accomplishment was writing an excel script to count up our trainees completed and uncompleted tasks for our weekly training report to the flight supervisors. This saved me so much time that I started scripting any repetitive tasks that I could to save myself more time and reduce errors. This is probably what sparked my interest in programming.

My earlier years I mostly worked on component level maintenance on many different avionics subsystems. This included radars, transmitters, electronic warfare modules, displays, navigation equipment, environmental sensors, payload controls, and targeting systems. I also helped maintained our test stations that we used to troubleshoot and fix all of these subsystems.

During my time at the USAF I completed my Associates in Applied Science for Avionic Systems.

About Me

Gosh where do I start???

Seriously though... things you should know about me:

I have a family, my wife Tracy and our son Sam. I love them very much. They are the reason why I am who I am today, and they give my life purpose and meaning.

Me, Tracy, and Sam (left to right)



I have a real passion for writing software and learning the different things you can accomplish with it. I often find myself tinkering in my spare time with an Arduino or Raspberry Pi just implementing things that I find interesting. I also tinker a little with Unity from time to time in an effort to make a game, but I have stalled out in the art phase so I have not done much with it.

I like movies, games, TV series, Linux!, programming, scripting, technology in general, craft beer, and dreaming big. I feel like I am pretty humble, likable, and in most instances relatable. I work well alone and as a team, and do not really have a preference as to which is better. There are pros and cons to both. Based on my experience thus far, I do think that most of the roles I have filled do work better with more people to complete the work. This is usually due to the amount of content that needs to be delivered and in the time frame it needs to be delivered.

Some things that I am looking for in my next job is to be part of a good team, to have my 15 year work history rewarded with reasonable vacation/PTO time, a competitive salary, and a good benefits package so I can care for my family. I also would like to work for a company who not only believes in work life balance, but practices decision making that actually afford those opportunities to their employees. I also think that inclusion in and out of the work place would be nice. There is a small group of us at my current employment that will attend after work gatherings at a local pub for craft beers. Its great to hang out with them outside the work environment, and builds a certain amount of comradery.

I think a more lax work environment would be nice, i.e. currently I can wear jeans and polo shirt to work. This is mainly due to the fact that you never know when you will have to go get in the mud and get on a machine for some activity. But the flexibility is nice.

One other thing I have been considering is a work from home job. A few years ago I would have been against it, but after 14+ years of commuting to work every day gains you a little perspective. That is a lot of wasted time! Especially if you could have completed the work from home. I can always make more money, but time on the other hand is becoming the more cherished commodity to me. Another thing I have been thinking about is working for a startup company. I understand it is more risky, but I would not mind the experience if for nothing more than gained perspective.

About This Project

This was a fairly fun project, and while I would like to spend more time perfecting it and adding more content to it, sadly I must bring development to a close in order to facilitate other projects that are on my to-do list, and more importantly start feeling out the local job market.

From a high level perspective this project simply uses HTML, CSS. and JavaScript. I utilized jQuery and bootstrap. For packaging up the content into a single file I used a simple make file in order to combine individual files into one large file. The web page was designed to be responsive in nature, simple yet scalable across devices.

I used asciidoctor to provide release notes.

I will be hosting this project on bitbucket. Please check it if you have time.

Of the experience I have learned thus far in life, this project only utilized a small portion.

I would have like to use react in this project, but alas I was too far into development to change it when I started tinkering with react. Overall I think this is a fairly simple project, intending to only provide a working demo of basic programming skills and information about me and my family. I hope you enjoyed it, and if something did not scale correctly or work right please let me know. I have not had the chance to test this in all browsers, and frankly is somewhat out of scope for the original project. For the best user experience I would recommend Safari or Chrome. I have done multiple browser support in the past, and while at times can be painful, it can be rewarding to see it work on multiple platforms. However, this project was not intended for that type of deployment.
